04015nam a22006375i 9780748683338DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212013stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486833387 a10.1515/97807486833382doi  a(DE-B1597)615765  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aPJ7745.J3bZ7885 2013 7aLIT0042202bisacsh04a892.71 aMontgomery, James E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAl-Jahiz :bIn Praise of Books /cJames E. Montgomery. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (592 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEdinburgh Studies in Classical Arabic Literature : ESCAL0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShortlisted for The Sheikh Zayed Book Award 2017Introduces the writings and ‘Abbasid-period textual world of Al-Jāhiz, the 'father of Arabic prose'Al-Jāhiz was a bibliomaniac, theologian, and spokesman for the political and cultural elite, a writer who lived, counselled and wrote in Iraq during the first century of the 'Abbasid caliphate. He advised, argued and rubbed shoulders with the major power brokers and leading religious and intellectual figures of his day, and crossed swords in debate and argument with the architects of the Islamic religious, theological, philosophical and cultural canon. His many, tumultuous writings engage with these figures, their ideas, theories and policies. They give us an invaluable but much-neglected window onto the values and beliefs of this cosmopolitan elite.Edinburgh University Press will publish two self-contained guides to reading al-Jāhiz that also shed light on his society and its writings. Volume 1, In Praise of Books, is devoted to bibliomania and al-Jāhiz’s bibliophilia. Volume 2, In Censure of Books, explores Al-Jāhiz's bibliophobia.Praise from the BRISMES Book Prize‘James E. Montgomery’s study must rank among the finest scholarly works on classical Arabic literature ever to have appeared in any language. I would in fact consider it to be the best I have come across.’ ‘Montgomery’s book is not only a work of great scholarship. Between the lines the reader can sense the story of an intense, long and deeply personal quest. It is that of a modern, Western intellect undertaking everything in its power to encounter, comprehend and elucidate one of the most complex and creative minds of the Islamic Middle Ages. The resulting sense of drama informs the writing on every page and turns the book into a human document of the first order.’  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aArabic literaturey750-1258xHistory and criticism. 0aBooks and readingzIslamic Empire. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074868333840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748683338423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748683338/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK